---
import GuideLayout from '../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro';
import { pmt, amortizeLoan } from '../../lib/loan.js';
const fmt = (n: number) => '$' + Math.round(n).toLocaleString('en-US');
const yrMo = (m: number) => `${Math.floor(m / 12)} yr ${m % 12} mo`;
const BAL = 10000, APR = 23;
const plans = [250, 350, 500].map((p) => {
  const a = amortizeLoan({ principal: BAL, annualRate: APR, payment: p });
  return { p, months: a.months, interest: a.totalInterest };
});
const bt = pmt(BAL * 1.04, 0, 18);
---

<GuideLayout
  title="How to Pay Off $10,000 of Credit Card Debt (Four Plans, Priced)"
  metaTitle="How to Pay Off $10k Credit Card Debt — 4 Plans Priced | Payoff Logic"
  description="Four realistic routes out of $10,000 at 23% APR — fixed payments, balance transfer, consolidation loan, and hybrid — each priced in months and interest."
  slug="pay-off-10k-credit-card"
  updated="July 11, 2026"
  updatedISO="2026-07-11"
  kind="payoff"
  tool={{ href: '/credit-card-payoff-calculator/', label: 'credit card payoff calculator' }}
>
  <div class="answer">
    <strong>Direct answer:</strong> At 23% APR, {fmt(BAL)} accrues about {fmt(BAL * 0.23 / 12)}
    of interest a month — so the plan is (1) stop new charges, (2) fix a payment of
    {fmt(plans[0].p)}–{fmt(plans[2].p)} (payoff in {yrMo(plans[2].months)}–{yrMo(plans[0].months)}),
    and (3) if your credit allows, cut the rate first with a 0% transfer or a
    consolidation loan — a 0% card cleared in 18 months needs about {fmt(bt)}/month
    and almost no interest beyond the fee.
  </div>

  <h2>Plan A: brute force with a fixed payment</h2>
  <div class="tablewrap"><table>
    <thead><tr><th>Fixed payment</th><th class="num">Time to zero</th><th class="num">Total interest</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {plans.map((r) => (
        <tr><td>{fmt(r.p)}/month</td><td class="num">{yrMo(r.months)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(r.interest)}</td></tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table></div>
  <p>
    No applications, no approvals — just the <a href="/guides/minimum-payments-trap/">fixed-payment
    fix</a> applied hard. The step from {fmt(250)} to {fmt(500)} cuts interest by
    {fmt(plans[0].interest - plans[2].interest)}; find your own ladder in the
    <a href="/credit-card-payoff-calculator/">payoff calculator</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan B: 0% balance transfer (credit ~670+)</h2>
  <p>
    Move the balance to a 0% card (12–21 months, 3–5% fee ≈ {fmt(BAL * 0.04)}). The
    entire game is finishing inside the window: {fmt(bt)}/month clears it in 18. Miss
    the window and deferred rates bite — set the payment on autopay on day one, and
    don't spend on the old card you just emptied.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan C: consolidation loan (predictability)</h2>
  <p>
    A personal loan at 11–14% swaps daily compounding for a fixed 36-month schedule —
    roughly {fmt(pmt(BAL * 1.03, 12, 36))}/month with the fee financed. It saves less
    than a well-executed transfer but can't be fumbled. Verify any specific offer
    against your cards in the <a href="/debt-consolidation-calculator/">consolidation
    calculator</a> — at the same monthly budget.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan D: the hybrid most people actually need</h2>
  <p>
    Transfer what fits the 0% limit, attack the remainder at the highest rate first
    (<a href="/guides/snowball-vs-avalanche/">avalanche</a>), and roll payments as
    pieces die. Two rules keep any plan alive: the cards stay at zero while you work,
    and windfalls (refunds, bonuses) go to the balance the day they land. {fmt(BAL)}
    at 23% feels permanent; every row above is an exit with a date on it.
  </p>
</GuideLayout>
